It does all of this with ONE pull of the handle.  I have read that after you get the hang of it it is common place to reload 250-300 bullets per hour.

title: For Sale:  Spotting Fake Listings On Armslist
postcontent:
Normally not one to clutter up space on armslist with non-adds but as there seems to be an increase in fraudulent listings I figured I'd toss out some tips for those somewhat inexperienced with this site.

--Always cross-reference a listing with what is selling on gunbroker.com.  The most popular fraudulent posts lift listings off of gunbroker complete with pictures and descriptions.  Often, but not always, attached pics will have the Gunbroker stamp on them which is a dead giveaway.  There are occasionally those who will dual list items legitimately, when that is the case the state of residence in the Gunbroker listing should be NC.  If you are ever unsure, contact the Gunbroker seller.

--Beware of ALL CAPS and poor language.  Not a hard and fast rule, but it should at least set off a few flags.

--Txt/Email is very convenient for many of us, but do not move forward with a sale without first talking to the seller over the phone.  If the seller is unwilling or unable to do so this should be another major red flag.

**Though many people will purchase firearms remotely and with success understand that you are really rolling the dice when doing so.  If you purchase a used firearm without first physically inspecting it you have nobody to blame but yourself if it turns out to be a paper weight.  If the seller is unable/unwilling to allow for proper physical inspection prior to purchase -- run away.  If you do not have the knowledge set to accurately assess a used firearm then find someone who does or save yourself the grief and buy new.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Lee Pro 1000 NiB 9mm and 45 LC plus many extras
postcontent:
Where to start..

I have a lee pro 1000 progressive reloading press.. I bought it last month with hopes of reloading 9mm.. It was out of stock every where but I happened to find one in stock for 45 long colt.. So I ordered it for 45LC.  I then went about ordering all of the parts to turn it into 9mm..  I had to buy:

9mm shell plate
Lee small primer attachment
Lee 9 mm dies( I have the 4 die set with factory crimp die.. As well as an extra powder through sizing die)
I also had to order small pistol case feed tube kit.
Also have the case collator 

I also ordered a .380 shell plate but could not find dies for it..
I have a digital grain scale to double check your work.
I have a bullet puller
I have a case tumbler and a full box of media
I have a hornady lock n load powder drop(haven't even taken out of the box..)
Several hundred 9mm and .380 once fired brass
1.5 pounds of bullseye powder..
Digital calipers to check length

I'm sure I'm missing stuff here..  It's all brand new.  I set up the press but have not used it..  I'm not sure if reloading is something I want to do.

This set is so complete, all you have to do is buy the dies to change it over.. I already ordered all the parts to let it take small and large cases and primers.

I spent hundreds of dollars and countless hours scouring the Internet to find these things in stock as they are sold out everywhere..  All you need to reload 9 mm is primers and bullets as I have powder too.  The same goes for 45 LC.

For those that don't know.. A progressive press like this does all the actions required to reload with one pull of the press..:it automatically feeds the cases into the machine; it deprimes, sizes it; then it reprimes, flares it to accept the bullet, measures and adds the powder; you place the bullet on the case and it seats the bullet, crimps it then ejects the completed round..  It does all of this with ONE pull of the handle.  I have read that after you get the hang of it it is common place to reload 250-300 bullets per hour.

I am interested in trading my entire set up.. Basically everything you need to start reloading minus primers and bullets.. For firearms.  I am most interested in assault style rifles such as sks's ak's ar15's..  I'm also interested in pistols..  Make me am offer.  Cash can be added or subtracted both ends to make it all work.

postcontent:
Russian Makarov high capacity Model IJ70, imported by Baikal, made in Russia in the Izhevsk factory. All matching numbers, wide Pearce grips, (1) double-stack 10 round magazine (rare) and pocket holster. Has some holster wear around the side of the muzzle, this gun is in good condition, very sturdy, very accurate and simple construction. Cleaned after each range time.  No longer exported by Russia. 
Markings:
Model IJ70-18AH = Most of the Russian Makarovs are new production and have either Baikal or Izhmech (IMEZ) markings, including "Made in Russia." Model numbers are typically IJ-70-18A. "18" is 9x18M caliber; "A" is the standard capacity; "H" is the high capacity (double stack magazine).
IMEZ = Izhevskii Mechanicheskii Zavod or Izhevsk Mechanical Factory located in the city of Izhevsk near the Ural Mountains, Russia.
K.B.I. = US Importer. KBI is located in Harrisburg, PA,
Baikal = is the name of a large lake in Siberia. It is also the trade name of Ishevsky Mechanichesky Zavod (SUP IMZ), a large Russian arms and ammunition manufacturing plant founded in 1942 as part of the Russian National Defence Industry to fight the invading Germans.
